industries and we won't all know exactly what you do. So yeah, we support, like I said, you know,

00:07:15.679 --> 00:07:21.679
some of it would be things you'd see everywhere. So, you know, supporting HR, you know, we do a

00:07:21.679 --> 00:07:28.000
lot of churn and attrition analysis, forecasting for hiring. Some of the construction specific

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:34.000
type stuff that we focus on then is, you know, safety is paramount. So predictive models to

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.799
understand, you know, relative safety on projects. When do we think projects will be at a higher risk

00:07:38.799 --> 00:07:45.679
based on, you know, previous factors about just the building itself, but, you know, the work

00:07:45.679 --> 00:07:51.679
that has led up to that point in time. And then a lot of stuff around, you know, resources,

00:07:51.679 --> 00:07:56.799
procurement, like how do we plan for projects effectively? Because if you think

00:07:56.799 --> 00:08:01.200
about, you know, especially for the GC part of the business, you know, there's a lot of stuff that goes

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:05.839
in planning. And then once a shovel goes in the ground, you're kind of set. Like, so you kind of

00:08:05.839 --> 00:08:12.000
plan accordingly. You make a pitch to an owner about what you're going to build for. So, like,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:15.040
as opposed to, like, usually when you do construction at your, you know, at your house,

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.799
where it's time and material. So if a contractor goes on forever, you kind of pay for it.

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:24.160
That is not how, you know, commercial construction generally works. You kind of

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:28.559
have a guaranteed maximum price, and that's what the owner is going to pay. So you want to make

00:08:28.559 --> 00:08:32.799
sure you plan accordingly and, you know, get a price that an owner will agree with, but also

00:08:32.799 --> 00:08:38.479
leaves you as much, you know, potential profit as possible. So a lot of support on the planning

00:08:38.479 --> 00:08:43.840
before a construction project starts, and then understanding, you know, the timeline and how

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:49.919
we think we're trending towards, you know, not eating away at that potential profit line once

00:08:49.919 --> 00:08:54.960
a shovel goes in the ground. Okay. I was thinking when you said, I feel like you said safety in

00:08:54.960 --> 00:09:00.559
there, and I was like safety, like physical safety, like construction safety. Are there

00:09:00.559 --> 00:09:05.440
two aspects to this, like risk safety and also physical safety? Yeah, so when we say it's safety,

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:08.640
we generally mean, like, on-site safety. So, like, you know, if there's going to be an incident, but

00:09:08.640 --> 00:09:13.280
then there is safety, like, you know, just insurance as well. That, which we generally

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:17.039
think of more of insurance, but I guess the insurance and risk, but there is, like, a safety,

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:23.440
I guess, a safety aspect to that as well. Okay. Yeah, I mean, I feel like construction is probably

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:29.599
one of the only places where analytics or data science would really go into physical human safety.

00:09:31.119 --> 00:09:35.919
In any way, I can't think of a lot of other industries besides maybe emergency services,

00:09:35.919 --> 00:09:39.599
right? Emergency responders that would be in that zone. That's really interesting.

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:46.479
I also am kind of wondering, I feel like I've heard you say that the construction industry is

00:09:46.479 --> 00:09:52.159
just sort of, do you feel like it's behind in analytics in general? Yeah. Why do you think that

00:09:52.159 --> 00:09:57.200
is? Even more broadly than analytics, like if you, I mean, you know, there's been multiple studies

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:03.039
done by, like, McKinsey and other places that, you know, a lot of the optimization and efficiencies

00:10:03.039 --> 00:10:07.200
that have been gained as computers have, like, worked their way into other industries have not

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:12.559
been realized in the construction industry. So, you know, I think the typical construction project

00:10:12.559 --> 00:10:21.599
runs 20% late and 80% over budget. And yeah, so it's due to a lot of factors. Like, if you look

00:10:21.599 --> 00:10:25.280
at the average, you know, I think one of the common ones people also always refer to, like,

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:31.359
Empire State Building was built in a year and 30 days or something. And, you know,

00:10:31.919 --> 00:10:36.799
building that size project today would, at best, you probably finish in maybe five years. So,

00:10:36.799 --> 00:10:41.280
you know, there's a lot of reasons for that. I mean, well, one of it is safety. Like, there's,

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:45.280
you know, fatalities in the Empire State Building and people are much more cognizant of safety.

00:10:45.280 --> 00:10:51.599
But I think generally the industry has been slow to adopt, even like standard stuff. Like,

00:10:51.599 --> 00:10:58.559
there's a lot of smaller, you know, construction firms that using pivot tables in Excel is almost

00:10:58.559 --> 00:11:03.599
like a bridge too far or, like, is, like, the edge of, like, how they interact with data. So,

00:11:04.559 --> 00:11:09.200
that's why, you know, some of the larger ones are definitely making forays into it. And then

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:14.000
there is, like, some, you know, construction tech. So, like, cool automation stuff. But, like, the

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.239
actual management of a project and, you know, just how you think about consuming data and using

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:22.559
data to make decisions has been very, very lacking. And I think some of it is just the

00:11:22.559 --> 00:11:26.159
logistics, like, right? Like, people on site, like, the last thing they want to do is pull up a

00:11:26.159 --> 00:11:32.080
laptop and, you know, and start looking at data that way. So, but also I think just the tool,

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:36.640
like, there's a lot of antiquated, you know, digital tools that, and they don't kind of easily

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:43.520
talk together either. Right. Jared in the comments just said, my dad works in construction and still

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:49.520
gets me to help with his Excel tables. I think if you're a data person, you have either sit there,

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:55.520
you're the person in everyone's life that helps them with Excel tables. Yeah. Well, speaking of

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:59.840
tech, what does your tech stack look like? Like, what did it look like when you came on board at

00:11:59.840 --> 00:12:06.400
Suffolk and have you sort of influenced it to change it to try to, like, modernize it and bring

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:11.919
more in? I mean, I will say, you know, again, like, relatively speaking, I was, when I came to

00:12:11.919 --> 00:12:16.320
Suffolk, you know, and talking and interviewing here, I was really, I was surprised, like, you

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:20.400
know, I saw the job posting. I think I saw it one or two times. I was like, I don't know. It doesn't

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:25.599
seem like, I'm not so sure. And then I applied and I interviewed. And at the time I interviewed

00:12:25.599 --> 00:12:32.159
my boss at that time was, so she's, she's chief data officer, so I was already surprised that

00:12:32.159 --> 00:12:36.479
they had, like, you know, someone at the, at the CEO, at the executive level with data in their

00:12:36.479 --> 00:12:44.640
title. So, and then, you know, talking to her, we, they even had, like, a data engineering team,

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:49.280
like, you know, a, you know, five to six person data engineering team, which was surprised, like,

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:52.479
it's bigger than other data engineering team places I've been that were, you know, supposedly

00:12:52.479 --> 00:12:58.960
data and digital focused. So they had invested quite heavily in resources. Most of the data to

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:04.559
that point, or, you know, how it manifested itself was data engineering for consuming data across all

00:13:04.559 --> 00:13:08.159
these disparate systems and mostly, like, data visualization. So we had, like, a tableau

00:13:08.159 --> 00:13:14.080
development team. So when I came in, in terms of, like, data science, like, most of the work that

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:19.760
we had done had been, it had grown very organically and there was no, like, enterprise grade kind of

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:25.760
infrastructure to build it. Like, we had, you know, one of our workflows was someone had, like,

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:31.280
uploaded an Excel sheet to, like, SharePoint, data engineering ingested into SharePoint and pushed

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:36.239
it down to Redshift and they ran an Alteryx flow that then, on a desktop, that wrote it back to,

00:13:36.239 --> 00:13:42.559
like, another Excel file that was then ingested into, like, another data platform. And so, you

00:13:42.559 --> 00:13:46.640
know, it was good work that I was doing. There was just, like, everything was different and kind of

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:52.559
very non-transparent. So when I came aboard, that's where I was, you know, so we run Databricks

00:13:52.559 --> 00:13:56.719
as a backend and we had just started to set up Databricks as a data warehouse, but the rest of our

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:02.719
kind of outward-facing tools were lagging. So being a fan of Posit, it seemed like a good

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:10.239
synergy for, you know, having a platform that would allow us to make our analysis mostly focused to

00:14:10.239 --> 00:14:15.520
start with, like, our analysis efforts more transparent and reproducible. So we started

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:20.640
with Workbench, quickly moved to incorporating Connect as well so we could, you know, the work

00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:24.880
that we did in Workbench, we could publish and have kind of, like, a repeatable workflow. So

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:30.799
we've stood that, you know, so from a tech stack, we have Databricks and the data science side,

00:14:30.799 --> 00:14:36.000
we do most of our stuff in Workbench and Connect. We also, obviously, I mentioned we do Tableau

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:42.880
for kind of standard dashboard visualizations. We also are just, like, Microsoft is very big in the

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:47.359
construction industry, so we're kind of, like, outside of the data team, we're kind of a Microsoft

00:14:47.359 --> 00:14:53.599
shop, so there's, like, some Power BI dashboards floating around as well. And then we've kind of

00:14:53.599 --> 00:14:57.359
delineated the line that's, like, anything that's, like, not static, we build either, like,

00:14:57.359 --> 00:15:03.599
you know, we build Shiny or Streamlit apps through Posit, and deploy through Posit Connect.

00:15:04.799 --> 00:15:10.719
And we're starting to move towards introducing a semantic layer, so we're, like, rolling out

00:15:10.719 --> 00:15:15.280
Cube, so we kind of have a standard interface for our metrics across the organization, because that's

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:21.280
been another one of the challenges, like, even not, you know, unique to us, where, you know,

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:25.919
maybe the metric that you see on Power BI that's supposed to be the same on Tableau is slightly

00:15:25.919 --> 00:15:30.239
different, so you spend the first 20 minutes of a 30-minute meeting under, like, trying to figure

00:15:30.239 --> 00:15:34.880
out what the nuance in that is, so we're trying to move all of that kind of logic as far back

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:41.440
upstream as possible, and, you know, kind of build out a more formal structure of a data model

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:47.919
in Databricks, and then use Cube to be, like, the interface for really all consumption layers.

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:53.440
Awesome. I have a, there's a question that came in anonymously on Slido

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:58.640
that really ties into this, so I figured I would take an opportunity to ask it now, which is,

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:04.239
how do you decide what to use Posit for, I'm guessing, like, Posit products, Workbench,

00:16:04.239 --> 00:16:08.000
Connect, stuff like that, and when to use those BI tools that you have access to?

00:16:09.919 --> 00:16:13.760
Yeah, so, I mean, I will say, like, what I wish would happen, and then, like,

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:19.840
what actually probably happens, which is probably, like, my hottest data take, which is,

00:16:20.880 --> 00:16:23.760
I mean, it's, like, two-sided. One is that, like, people,

00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:27.520
most orgs move, like, way too quickly to dashboards, because people say they want

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:32.320
to get involved in data, and, like, the most tangible way that you think about data is a

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:37.440
dashboard, so, you know, you end up building a lot of dashboards that once people start using them,

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:43.919
they, you know, the value is maybe not there, so I always prefer to, like, do more kind of bespoke

00:16:43.919 --> 00:16:46.880
analysis, and then when you get to the point of understanding what is really important to

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:52.320
the business, like, that is what you codify and put into a dashboard, so you have, like, fewer

00:16:52.320 --> 00:16:55.840
dashboards, but they're more meaningful, because they kind of measure the things that are more

00:16:55.840 --> 00:17:01.520
important to the business, so that is how, like, I would draw the line. I mean, I feel like you

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:06.160
need to meet people, you need to meet your business stakeholders, like, where they are,

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:11.520
like, just all of a sudden standing up a bunch of dashboards, especially if they have, like,

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:17.359
no context, you know, data, I mean, construction, Suffolk in particular being a really good example

00:17:17.359 --> 00:17:21.359
that, you know, people went from, like, no dashboards to all of a sudden, you know, three

00:17:21.359 --> 00:17:26.400
dozen Tableau dashboards, and then just trying to navigate their way through that is not super

00:17:26.400 --> 00:17:30.800
helpful, so, you know, sometimes things that are in a dashboard, if it's, like, you know,

00:17:31.199 --> 00:17:35.439
if there is no need to filter and the data is not that dynamic, maybe you just do, like,

00:17:35.439 --> 00:17:39.040
exception reportings that you send through email, so, like, we're trying to move that kind of stuff

00:17:39.040 --> 00:17:42.160
to Posit, right, like, does it need to be a dashboard, do you need to interact with it,

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:47.920
or is it just I want to get a notification when this thing changes below a certain threshold,

00:17:47.920 --> 00:17:52.640
and, like, so we look to, like, move and automate that stuff through, you know,

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:59.119
Porto and emails and scheduling through Connect, so that is one aspect, and then kind of, like,

00:17:59.119 --> 00:18:06.160
more broadly, our guidelines are, like, if it's just tabular static data that people want to pivot

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:10.319
and filter, like, that would be a BI dashboard, but if it's something that, like, you need more

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:16.560
interactive calculations or, you know, any kind of interacting with a model or other API, we usually

00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:21.359
look to build something, you know, custom through and deploy through Connect.

00:18:22.239 --> 00:18:26.160
Awesome, yeah, lots of, lots more flexibility when you can do it that way, for sure.

00:18:27.119 --> 00:18:32.880
Well, I have some amazing Slido questions that are getting upvoted. Zach asked a great question.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:37.839
It's got asterisks next to it, so I'm going to ask it for him, and it says the Empire State

00:18:37.839 --> 00:18:43.199
Building didn't have a lot of precedent for it. That's very true, and I hadn't thought about that.

00:18:43.199 --> 00:18:48.640
Does the construction industry have issues with a lack of historical data for new projects that

00:18:48.640 --> 00:18:54.560
are really ambitious like that, I'm guessing? Yeah, so, I mean, even, like, you know, the Empire

00:18:54.959 --> 00:19:00.719
State Building itself, like, even given that, you know, the, there's the construction project

00:19:00.719 --> 00:19:04.880
itself, like, how complex is the building, but then as more buildings get built, like, get built,

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:11.119
like, even just where you're working becomes, you know, the challenges of that are compounded as

00:19:11.119 --> 00:19:15.599
well. So, I think, I forget what someone, I was talking to someone here, one of our estimators,

00:19:15.599 --> 00:19:19.040
and I forget, I want, I don't want to say what the number is exactly, but, you know,

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:25.760
building in Boston, about, like, 40 percent of the budget is, you know, just moving materials

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:33.680
around or getting in or off site because the access is so limited. So, you know, there's,

00:19:33.680 --> 00:19:38.079
and there's no data for that, like, to account for that, but, like, even to your basic question,

00:19:38.079 --> 00:19:44.479
yeah, there's definitely a lot of challenge with historical data. You know, we generally think

00:19:44.479 --> 00:19:48.959
we're pretty good about data relative to the rest of the construction industry, and we do have a lot

00:19:48.959 --> 00:19:53.760
of it, but, you know, some of the tools, especially if you think about scheduled data,

00:19:53.760 --> 00:20:01.199
they use, it's a tool that's now owned by Oracle. Primavera P6 is, like, the, like, go-to, like,

00:20:01.839 --> 00:20:06.719
and that is, you know, it's owned by Oracle, like, most Oracle stuff. It doesn't seem like it's been

00:20:06.719 --> 00:20:13.280
touched in 25 or 30 years. So, there's not a lot of great ways to get data out. It's kind of very

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:17.520
messy, and then how people set up their projects are always different. So, like, looking for,

00:20:17.520 --> 00:20:22.479
like, a through line between a project that was stood up 25 years ago and how,

00:20:22.479 --> 00:20:27.199
you know, a project is built today, there's not a lot of continuity in that data.

00:20:28.319 --> 00:20:33.760
Yeah. I guess that's the same problem that everybody has, is that historical trends don't

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:38.800
always equal future projections, right? And once we got past COVID, I think we all realized that

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:43.439
that was true in a really big way, that nothing would ever be the same again. And I feel like

00:20:43.439 --> 00:20:50.239
COVID, well, and also just supply chain things that were happening during that time,

00:20:50.239 --> 00:20:54.079
really changed construction with construction material costs. Is that something that

00:20:54.800 --> 00:21:00.160
you had to deal with or the aftermath of that when you came on? Because you came on to Suffolk

00:21:00.160 --> 00:21:06.479
in 2023, right? Yeah. So, we're, like, so it's, you know, right on the heels of COVID, basically.

00:21:07.839 --> 00:21:12.160
But all the projects that took place then, I mean, some of them, I mean, we actually have

00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:17.040
done a good job. Like, they actually went back and, you know, coded a lot of the stuff. Because

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:20.640
there's even just some costs that were, like, additional costs that were associated with

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:26.160
projects or additional PPE that they needed during the COVID time that, you know, all else being

00:21:26.160 --> 00:21:31.359
equal would even then skew the data about how that project performed relative to the before time. So,

00:21:31.359 --> 00:21:37.359
we've done a good job of, like, trying to identify some of that and excluding it. But even just more

00:21:37.359 --> 00:21:42.160
broadly, like, yeah, like, the second or third order effects are, you know, not as explicit and

00:21:42.160 --> 00:21:48.560
much harder to identify. I will say, like, the procurement and supply chain, it obviously

00:21:48.560 --> 00:21:57.920
affects us. Suffolk as a GC, generally speaking, is somewhat shielded from those costs. Like,

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:01.680
they're either, you know, on the owner or on the subcontractor. But it does affect, like,

00:22:01.680 --> 00:22:05.040
the overall schedule. So, you know, it's not something that we can completely ignore. But,

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:10.160
yeah, like, that is always a constant. All right, people want to look at historical data. Like,

00:22:10.160 --> 00:22:13.920
you just put a big asterisk for the three years that we were doing, you know, COVID-related

00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:18.719
projects and carve them out or, like, just make note of, like, how they change it. And we don't

00:22:18.719 --> 00:22:24.000
have, like, a hard and fast rule for how we do it. It really – I hate to be, like, you know,

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.839
you kind of look at it and make a judgment. But, you know, that ultimately is – because, like,

00:22:27.839 --> 00:22:32.239
that's the other thing, too. Like, you know, construction, we're rather large. But if you

00:22:32.239 --> 00:22:38.719
think about the unit of measure being a project itself, you know, and at the scale that we usually

00:22:38.719 --> 00:22:45.199
do most of our analysis, there's, you know, maybe only 30 or 40, maybe a part of 60, you know,

00:22:45.199 --> 00:22:48.880
projects that finish in a given year, right? The lifecycle of a project being, like, three years

00:22:48.880 --> 00:22:53.839
that, you know, at that level, it's kind of small sample sizes all over the place.

00:22:53.839 --> 00:22:58.640
Oh, wow. That's such a long time horizon because inflation changes a ton even over three years.

00:22:58.640 --> 00:23:03.119
All right. Well, enough of my nosy inflation questions. There's a lot of really good questions

00:23:03.119 --> 00:23:07.520
on Slido. Reminder for everybody, if you've just hopped on, we're asking questions in Slido today,

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:11.839
which is actually pretty cool because you get to upvote stuff. And I'm loving seeing what kind of

00:23:11.839 --> 00:23:15.920
rises to the top. So, we have an anonymous question that has risen to the top of our Slido.

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:22.640
And it says, do you get pushback from site managers who place more trust in their subjective

00:23:22.640 --> 00:23:27.520
experience than what the data is telling you? And if so, how do you get buy-in from those people?

00:23:29.599 --> 00:23:34.479
Yes, 100%. And, you know, I wouldn't even say, like, I don't know if I frame it as pushback.

00:23:34.479 --> 00:23:41.040
A lot of it is just, like, they know better, right? Like, you know, there's nuance in the

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:45.040
actual management of a project that is not captured in the data that we have available. So,

00:23:46.640 --> 00:23:50.880
generally, what we want to do before we roll anything out is kind of, you know, identify

00:23:51.760 --> 00:23:57.680
site managers, superintendents, PXs, people who have more intimate knowledge of projects

00:23:57.680 --> 00:24:04.319
themselves to get their insight and feedback on what we're doing before we go roll something out.

00:24:04.319 --> 00:24:09.280
And I will say, I hope we've done a better job since I've started, but that has, I think, been,

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:13.119
again, probably not specific to Suffolk. But one of our big challenges here is that,

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:17.920
you know, we've done a lot of good technical work, like the 80% of getting the technical work done,

00:24:17.920 --> 00:24:21.520
and then we've really dropped the ball on the last 20% work, which is, like, you know,

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:26.719
what's the productization of this? Like, how do you get end users in a way that it makes sense to

00:24:26.719 --> 00:24:31.520
them? Some of it is as simple as, like, how you label it. Like, when we rolled out, like, you know,

00:24:31.520 --> 00:24:35.439
the example I gave before where we called it, like, the safety model, it somehow morphed into,

00:24:35.439 --> 00:24:40.479
like, and the way the data was presented, like, it was kind of like you have a higher

00:24:40.479 --> 00:24:45.520
likelihood of incident. So, it turned in from, it turned, the initial rollout turned from something

00:24:45.520 --> 00:24:50.479
being, you know, helpful or useful to, like, a list you wanted to avoid, and that actually

00:24:50.479 --> 00:24:56.319
would impact how people collected data and, you know, tuned out the results just by the way that

00:24:56.319 --> 00:25:00.959
we framed up with what the solution was. So, you know, a lot of lessons that we've learned there,

00:25:00.959 --> 00:25:06.719
which is the technology itself, whether, you know, the model building itself is, you know,

00:25:07.599 --> 00:25:11.920
maybe at most, like, 50% of the problem. The rest of it is, like, how do you roll it out and make

00:25:11.920 --> 00:25:17.119
it something that, you know, communicate with your end users so they understand what you're doing and

00:25:18.959 --> 00:25:23.439
how it can best, you know, how it can best make them more efficient at their job. It's not

00:25:23.439 --> 00:25:28.479
something that we're trying to use data to be big brother and flag people for things that are

00:25:28.479 --> 00:25:34.800
beyond their control. So, yeah. So, I mean, that is, like, a constant evolution. So, like, that is,

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:40.000
broadly speaking, is, like, we do try to do a better job of partnering with our strategic business

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:44.640
stakeholders so they can be part of, like, how we roll solutions out. But the other one is just,

00:25:44.640 --> 00:25:48.239
I mean, we're kind of going eyes wide open knowing that the data that we currently have,

00:25:48.800 --> 00:25:54.479
there's probably additional data that we would need that would give us more nuanced insights,

00:25:54.479 --> 00:25:57.760
and then partnering with, like, just people who are on the job sites to figure out how we can

00:25:57.760 --> 00:26:02.800
actually collect that level of detail that we need. So, when we iterate on these, you know,

00:26:03.599 --> 00:26:07.199
whatever the data product is, again, that we think we're improving because we've now captured

00:26:07.199 --> 00:26:13.040
additional fidelity in the data. Yeah, that's awesome. Well, I have another fantastic question

00:26:13.040 --> 00:26:18.000
from Slido that has been upvoted a ton. It's from Tony. Tony, are you available to answer that?

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:31.199
I'm going to jump in and ask. Let's see. Maybe I caught Tony off guard. I see Tony tried to unmute,

00:26:31.199 --> 00:26:38.239
but there you are. Oh, there we are. Okay. Hi, Tony. My video wasn't coming on. Yeah,

00:26:38.239 --> 00:26:46.239
I'd just like to hear a little bit about where you might be using AI in the process of budgeting or

00:26:46.800 --> 00:26:54.000
trying to figure out maybe where cost overruns are likely to happen or where you can build in

00:26:54.560 --> 00:27:01.680
to your budget to try to ensure you'll have some profit margin in the long run, or even,

00:27:02.319 --> 00:27:07.920
especially here in the Boston area, the types of customers that are more profitable, higher ed

00:27:07.920 --> 00:27:17.439
versus healthcare versus government, things like that, and which AI tools or products you're using.

00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:26.479
Yeah, sure. Great question. So, you know, I would say, so Suffolk, one of the maybe benefits of

00:27:26.479 --> 00:27:33.439
Suffolk is we are still private. So John Fish, you know, founded Suffolk and still leads it,

00:27:33.439 --> 00:27:38.400
and he is a big proponent of data, and this past year has made kind of a

00:27:39.439 --> 00:27:43.680
corporate-wide edict. I mean, I look at the sign across the street, it says we're aiming to be the

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:50.160
future leader of AI in the built world. So it's kind of like a company-wide initiative to figure

00:27:50.160 --> 00:27:55.280
out how we can best leverage AI. So the way that, you know, over the past year it's kind of taken

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:59.920
shape, there are sort of two flavors of it. One is kind of what you would imagine what everyone's

00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:05.920
doing, which is, all right, we have a bunch of SOPs or PDFs somewhere, so like let's throw like

00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:10.719
those in one that we can build a bunch of chat agents that are, you know, does rag to retrieve

00:28:10.719 --> 00:28:17.359
specific information about particular domains. That one's less exciting. But the other areas

00:28:17.359 --> 00:28:21.839
that we're looking to do it, I mean, there's kind of two large ones, and it's actually in

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:27.760
not necessarily either of the ones that you identified, but we're doing in the design,

00:28:27.760 --> 00:28:33.280
like how can we use AI to augment and speed along design of buildings themselves,

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:38.959
and then in the planning of projects. So can we, as I mentioned before, like the kind of

00:28:40.239 --> 00:28:47.359
planning tool that is the industry-wide standard, P6 Primavera, is very antiquated,

00:28:49.040 --> 00:28:53.119
and it takes, you know, so just from a user experience perspective, it's not very intuitive

00:28:53.119 --> 00:29:00.400
or friendly, and where we think we can like gain a lot of efficiencies is automated using AI to

00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:06.560
kind of, if not create an entire schedule, you know, take something that it may take a plan or

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:13.920
two weeks now and get them 80% of the way there in a manner of minutes or hours even. So those are

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:20.319
kind of some of the big areas of focus, and then kind of maybe in between area where we've seen a

00:29:20.319 --> 00:29:27.280
lot of traction is in data transformation. So like we have a lot of data in PDF, so as part of

00:29:27.280 --> 00:29:31.760
our data pipeline, can we use AI to like extract information out of that and turn it into tabular

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:39.359
formats as part of our data warehouse? So we've picked up a lot of stuff like that. So I honestly,

00:29:39.359 --> 00:29:44.560
like in the past two or three months, like I feel like, you know, a year ago everyone was really

00:29:44.560 --> 00:29:49.439
trying to force AI and like put it in, you know, as a square peg in a bunch of round holes, and I

00:29:49.439 --> 00:29:56.880
think over the past month, like we've had like a bunch of really smart and novel use cases come

00:29:56.880 --> 00:30:04.000
up. Like literally, I think just this past week one of my colleagues built, he has an AI bot that,

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:10.079
or an AI agent that looks at GitHub submissions. So basically like looks for any changes to our

00:30:10.079 --> 00:30:16.319
data model and then goes and looks through all our GitHub repos and like figures out any references

00:30:16.319 --> 00:30:20.800
to it and like find out the products that are associated with it. So we can send notifications

00:30:20.800 --> 00:30:26.560
to say, you know, this change to this data model is going to have a potential impact to these

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:34.560
products downstream. So yeah, so I think, you know, I think probably still in the short term,

00:30:34.560 --> 00:30:40.560
aside from like those two outward facing ones, a lot of the efficiencies that we're gaining are

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:48.000
more upstream in the data pipeline side at the moment. And then, oh, in terms of what we use. So

00:30:49.040 --> 00:30:53.280
as I mentioned, like from an enterprise agreement, we kind of have a partnership with Microsoft. So

00:30:53.280 --> 00:30:59.680
we started using, you know, the Microsoft Azure suite of open AI integration. Since then we've

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:04.400
been, you know, we've been tasked, we've been given the ability to kind of pilot other ones as

00:31:04.400 --> 00:31:12.319
well. So Databricks has their own native LLM. So we use that somewhat. We're kind of looking

00:31:12.319 --> 00:31:18.560
or maybe potentially piloting. So we have a bunch of people using individual open AI,

00:31:18.560 --> 00:31:22.640
like business accounts, but so looking to consolidate that potentially as enterprise

00:31:22.640 --> 00:31:29.520
as well and try that. And then maybe we're, maybe again, some individuals have used Gemini as well

00:31:29.520 --> 00:31:34.239
and make, we might look to make that more and more formal as well. So really like trying to

00:31:34.239 --> 00:31:37.680
run the gamut, whatever's out there, like we're, it's kind of like the wild west still in terms of

00:31:37.680 --> 00:31:42.959
technology, like trying to figure out which one works best for which scenario. I think we can

00:31:42.959 --> 00:31:48.560
all relate to that. Thank you for the amazing question, Tony. Great, thanks. I have a question,

00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:54.319
and I think that Jeffrey Silverman's question on Slido kind of rolls in with mine. So Jeffrey

00:31:54.319 --> 00:32:00.959
had asked like, you know, the construction industry is hesitant to implement new tech and

00:32:00.959 --> 00:32:05.839
data science analytics. So do you find that folks at the company are resistant to your work? And I

00:32:05.839 --> 00:32:10.000
know that we had talked a little bit about like getting people to trust you. My question is,

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:16.079
how important is it to have an executive like you've got that's championing data science efforts?

00:32:16.079 --> 00:32:20.719
And is there any advice that you have for people who are sort of in that battle right now where

00:32:20.719 --> 00:32:26.880
they're trying to get executive champions on board? Yeah, so I will say, I mean, that is

00:32:26.880 --> 00:32:36.719
probably the biggest lesson I've learned over my career. I was like, I mean, my somewhat snarky,

00:32:36.719 --> 00:32:40.719
not snarky answer is like, you know, the best way to do it is to, when you're looking for a job,

00:32:40.719 --> 00:32:46.239
find a place that already has that infrastructure built in. Because I will say that has been like

00:32:47.040 --> 00:32:50.959
my biggest challenge in my career. Like, you know, you talk to somebody who's really about

00:32:50.959 --> 00:32:55.520
all about data, like they're the hiring manager, and then you get hired in, and maybe they're like

00:32:55.520 --> 00:32:59.040
a senior manager or director, depending on what, like, if that's as high as it goes, and then,

00:32:59.599 --> 00:33:03.119
you know, they could have buy-in, but that doesn't mean that they have buy-in from

00:33:03.119 --> 00:33:07.280
whomever is above them. So I, whenever I would interview, I would always ask like,

00:33:07.280 --> 00:33:11.439
what's the highest role of somebody who has data in their title? And like, that would kind of,

00:33:12.079 --> 00:33:19.520
to me, be a proxy for like, how bought-in are you on actually using data? But otherwise, you know,

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:23.280
you kind of go down the same path that you normally always do, which is like, all right,

00:33:23.280 --> 00:33:26.479
you find your strategic business partner, you like get your small wins, and then you

00:33:27.199 --> 00:33:31.520
fight for a budget. But I wish I had a better answer. But like, to me, like, there is no

00:33:34.640 --> 00:33:39.359
shortcut to it if you don't have people who, I mean, you know, you can, I've been places where

00:33:39.359 --> 00:33:44.239
you can take individual data wins to, like, people at the C-level or even right below the

00:33:44.239 --> 00:33:48.959
C-level, but unless it's like a company-wide, like, edict, like, I find it really challenging

00:33:48.959 --> 00:33:54.160
for everyone to just, for it always to be, like, top of mind and not something that will get cut

00:33:54.160 --> 00:33:59.280
as soon as, you know, those are the type of decisions that need to be made. So I wish I

00:33:59.280 --> 00:34:03.199
had a more optimistic answer for it, but like, there, like, I think, you know, they're, obviously,

00:34:03.199 --> 00:34:06.959
like, you kind of have to understand the scope of the battle that you're trying to fight. And if

00:34:07.839 --> 00:34:11.760
it is that, like, I'm a manager who's come in and, like, I only have a director above me, then,

00:34:12.639 --> 00:34:17.919
who believes in my vision, but, like, you know, then thinking you're going to be able to get a

00:34:19.199 --> 00:34:26.000
budget that to implement something, you know, enterprise-wide out of the gate is kind of,

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:29.840
that's more like a three- or four- or five-year play, even. So you kind of have to understand,

00:34:29.840 --> 00:34:36.560
like, how high up you have approval on, and then, like, kind of fight your battles and work your

00:34:36.560 --> 00:34:40.879
plan from there, because I don't think there is a shortcut to go from, we only have buy-in at the,

00:34:40.879 --> 00:34:45.760
like, manager level all the way up to, like, C-suite buy-in. Yeah, that's not something that's

00:34:45.760 --> 00:34:50.560
going to turn around in a couple of months or even maybe a couple of years. Yeah. All right.

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:56.000
Thank you so much for those insights and fantastic question from Jeffrey. I have an anonymous

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:00.800
question that is next in our sort of vote on Slido reminder. We're doing questions in Slido,

00:35:00.800 --> 00:35:04.639
and you could vote on them, which is super fun watching them sort of, like, pop around my screen.

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:11.520
So the question is, are there established practices for sharing data across businesses

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:16.719
in construction, or do you only have to rely on your own company's data only?

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:24.560
Yeah. So there are no established practices. I mean, I would say even, not even across businesses,

00:35:24.560 --> 00:35:29.679
even within businesses, there's very little established practice for sharing data. So

00:35:30.080 --> 00:35:36.320
unfortunately, there's not. I mean, there are tools that, you know, construction management

00:35:36.320 --> 00:35:42.239
tools that allow, you know, multiple different people to kind of access from a operational

00:35:42.239 --> 00:35:48.719
perspective the same data, like Procore is a big one. And, you know, you can have, like, a GC like

00:35:48.719 --> 00:35:52.800
us and subcontractors, like, having, or even owners having access to that same instance.

